# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: parametric-polymorphism
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Generic programming was introduced to the mainstream with Ada in 1977.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] With templates in C++, generic programming became part of the repertoire of professional library design.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] The techniques were further improved and *parameterized types* were introduced in the influential 1994 book *Design Patterns*.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] New techniques were introduced by Andrei Alexandrescu in his 2001 book *Modern C++ Design: Generic Programming and Design Patterns Applied*.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Subsequently, D implemented the same ideas.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Such software entities are known as *generics* in Ada, C#, Delphi, Eiffel, F#, Java, Mojo, Nim, Python, Go, Rust, Swift, TypeScript, and Visual Basic (.NET).
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] They are known as *parametric polymorphism* in ML, Scala, Julia, and Haskell.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] The "generic programming" paradigm is an approach to software decomposition whereby fundamental requirements on types are abstracted from across concrete examples of algorithms and data structures and formalized as concepts, analogously to the abstraction of algebraic theories in abstract algebra.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Early examples of this programming approach were implemented in Scheme and Ada, although the best known example is the Standard Template Library (STL), which developed a theory of iterators that is used to decouple sequence data structures and the algorithms operating on them.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] For example, given *N* sequence data structures, e.g. singly linked list, vector etc., and *M* algorithms to operate on them, e.g.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] `find`, `sort` etc., a direct approach would implement each algorithm specifically for each data structure, giving *N* × *M* combinations to implement.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Thus, only *N* + *M* data structure-algorithm combinations need be implemented.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] An important point is that a data structure will return a model of the most general concept that can be implemented efficiently—computational complexity requirements are explicitly part of the concept definition.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] This limits the data structures a given algorithm can be applied to and such complexity requirements are a major determinant of data structure choice.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Generic programming similarly has been applied in other domains, e.g. graph algorithms.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Although this approach often uses language features of compile-time genericity and templates, it is independent of particular language-technical details.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] — Alexander Stepanov, An Interview with A.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Other programming paradigms that have been described as generic programming include *Datatype generic programming* as described in "Generic Programming – an Introduction".
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] The *Scrap your boilerplate* approach is a lightweight generic programming approach for Haskell.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] In this article we distinguish the high-level programming paradigms of *generic programming*, above, from the lower-level programming language *genericity mechanisms* used to implement them (see Programming language support for genericity).
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] For further discussion and comparison of generic programming paradigms, see.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Genericity facilities have existed in high-level languages since at least the 1970s in languages such as ML, CLU and Ada, and were subsequently adopted by many object-based and object-oriented languages, including BETA, C++, D, Eiffel, Java, and DEC's now defunct Trellis-Owl.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Genericity is implemented and supported differently in various programming languages; the term "generic" has also been used differently in various programming contexts.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] For example, in Forth the compiler can execute code while compiling and one can create new *compiler keywords* and new implementations for those words on the fly.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] It has few *words* that expose the compiler behaviour and therefore naturally offers *genericity* capacities that, however, are not referred to as such in most Forth texts.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] The term has been used in functional programming, specifically in Haskell-like languages, which use a structural type system where types are always parametric and the actual code on those types is generic.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] These uses still serve a similar purpose of code-saving and rendering an abstraction.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Arrays and structs can be viewed as predefined generic types.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Every usage of an array or struct type instantiates a new concrete type, or reuses a previous instantiated type.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Array element types and struct element types are parameterized types, which are used to instantiate the corresponding generic type.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] All this is usually built-in in the compiler and the syntax differs from other generic constructs.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Some extensible programming languages try to unify built-in and user defined generic types.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] A broad survey of genericity mechanisms in programming languages follows.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] For a specific survey comparing suitability of mechanisms for generic programming, see.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] When creating container classes in statically typed languages, it is inconvenient to write specific implementations for each datatype contained, especially if the code for each datatype is virtually identical.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Above, `T` is a placeholder for whatever type is specified when the list is created.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] These "generic objects of type `T`", commonly called templates, allow a class to be reused with different datatypes as long as certain contracts such as subtypes and signature are kept.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] This genericity mechanism should not be confused with *inclusion polymorphism*, which is the algorithmic usage of exchangeable sub-classes: for instance, a list of objects of type `MovingEntity` containing objects of type `Animal` and `Car`.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] The C++ `template` construct used above is widely cited as the genericity construct that popularized the notion among programmers and language designers and supports many generic programming idioms.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] The D language also offers fully generic-capable templates based on the C++ precedent but with a simplified syntax.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] The Java language has provided genericity facilities syntactically based on C++'s since the introduction of Java Platform, Standard Edition (J2SE) 5.0.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] C# 2.0, Oxygene 1.5 (formerly Chrome) and Visual Basic (.NET) 2005 have constructs that exploit the support for generics present in Microsoft .NET Framework since version 2.0.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Ada has had generics since it was first designed in 1977–1980.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] The standard library uses generics to provide many services.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Ada 2005 adds a comprehensive generic container library to the standard library, which was inspired by C++'s Standard Template Library.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] A *generic unit* is a package or a subprogram that takes one or more *generic formal parameters*.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] A *generic formal parameter* is a value, a variable, a constant, a type, a subprogram, or even an instance of another, designated, generic unit.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] For generic formal types, the syntax distinguishes between discrete, floating-point, fixed-point, access (pointer) types, etc.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Some formal parameters can have default values.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] To *instantiate* a generic unit, the programmer passes *actual* parameters for each formal.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] The generic instance then behaves just like any other unit.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] It is possible to instantiate generic units at run-time, for example, inside a loop.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] The language syntax allows precise specification of constraints on generic formal parameters.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] For example, it is possible to specify that a generic formal type will only accept a modular type as the actual.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] In this example, `Array_Type` is constrained by both `Index_Type` and `Element_Type`.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] When instantiating the unit, the programmer must pass an actual array type that satisfies these constraints.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] The disadvantage of this fine-grained control is a complicated syntax, but, because all generic formal parameters are completely defined in the specification, the compiler can instantiate generics without looking at the body of the generic.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Unlike C++, Ada does not allow specialised generic instances, and requires that all generics be instantiated explicitly.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] C++ uses templates to enable generic programming techniques.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] The C++ Standard Library includes the Standard Template Library or STL that provides a framework of templates for common data structures and algorithms.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Templates in C++ may also be used for template metaprogramming, which is a way of pre-evaluating some of the code at compile-time rather than run-time.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Using template specialization, C++ Templates are Turing complete.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] There are many kinds of templates, the most common being function templates and class templates.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] A *function template* is a pattern for creating ordinary functions based upon the parameterizing types supplied when instantiated.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] For example, the C++ Standard Template Library contains the function template `std::max(x, y)` that creates functions that return either `x` or `y`, whichever is larger.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] The compiler examines the arguments used to call `max` and determines that this is a call to `max(int, int)`.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] This works whether the arguments `x` and `y` are integers, strings, or any other type for which the expression `x < y` is sensible, or more specifically, for any type for which `operator<` is defined.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Common inheritance is not needed for the set of types that can be used, and so it is very similar to duck typing.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] A program defining a custom data type can use operator overloading to define the meaning of `<` for that type, thus allowing its use with the `std::max()` function template.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] While this may seem a minor benefit in this isolated example, in the context of a comprehensive library like the STL it allows the programmer to get extensive functionality for a new data type, just by defining a few operators for it.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Merely defining `<` allows a type to be used with the standard `std::sort()`, `std::stable_sort()`, and `std::binary_search()` algorithms or to be put inside data structures such as `std::set<T>`s (equivalent to `TreeSet<T>`, heaps, and associative arrays.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] C++ templates are completely type safe at compile time.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] As a demonstration, the standard type `std::complex<T>` does not define the `<` operator, because there is no strict order on complex numbers.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Therefore, `std::max(x, y)` will fail with a compile error, if `x` and `y` are `complex` values.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Likewise, other templates that rely on `<` cannot be applied to `complex` data unless a comparison (in the form of a functor or function) is provided.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] For instance, `std::complex<T>` cannot be used as key for a `std::map<K, V>` (equivalent to `TreeMap<K, V>`) unless a comparison is provided.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Unfortunately, compilers historically generate somewhat esoteric, long, and unhelpful error messages for this sort of error.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Ensuring that a certain object adheres to a method protocol can alleviate this issue.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Languages which use `std::compare` instead of `<` can also use `std::complex<T>` values as keys.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Another kind of template, a *class template*, extends the same concept to classes.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] A class template specialization is a class.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Class templates are often used to make generic containers.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] For example, the STL has a doubly linked list container, `std::list<T>` (equivalent to `LinkedList<T>`).
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] To make a linked list of integers, one writes `list<int>`, while a list of strings is denoted `list<string>`.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] A `std::list<T>` has a set of standard functions associated with it, that work for any compatible parameterizing types.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] C++20 introduces constraining template types using concepts.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] A powerful feature of C++'s templates is *template specialization*.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] This allows alternative implementations to be provided based on certain characteristics of the parameterized type that is being instantiated.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Template specialization has two purposes: to allow certain forms of optimization, and to reduce code bloat.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] For example, consider a `sort()` template function.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] One of the primary activities that such a function does is to swap or exchange the values in two of the container's positions.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] If the values are large (in terms of the number of bytes it takes to store each of them), then it is often quicker to first build a separate list of pointers to the objects, sort those pointers, and then build the final sorted sequence.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] If the values are quite small however it is usually fastest to just swap the values in-place as needed.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Furthermore, if the parameterized type is already of some pointer-type, then there is no need to build a separate pointer array.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Template specialization allows the template creator to write different implementations and to specify the characteristics that the parameterized type(s) must have for each implementation to be used.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Unlike function templates, class templates can be partially specialized.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] That means that an alternate version of the class template code can be provided when some of the template parameters are known, while leaving other template parameters generic.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] This can be used, for example, to create a default implementation (the *primary specialization*) that assumes that copying a parameterizing type is expensive and then create partial specializations for types that are cheap to copy, thus increasing overall efficiency.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Clients of such a class template just use specializations of it without needing to know whether the compiler used the primary specialization or some partial specialization in each case.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Class templates can also be *fully specialized,* which means that an alternate implementation can be provided when all of the parameterizing types are known.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Some uses of templates, such as the `max()` function, were formerly filled by function-like preprocessor macros (a legacy of the C language).
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Macros are expanded (copy pasted) by the preprocessor, before program compiling; templates are actual real functions.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Macros are always expanded inline; templates can also be inline functions when the compiler deems it appropriate.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] However, templates are generally considered an improvement over macros for these purposes.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Templates avoid some of the common errors found in code that makes heavy use of function-like macros, such as evaluating parameters with side effects twice.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Perhaps most importantly, templates were designed to be applicable to much larger problems than macros.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Many compilers historically had poor support for templates, thus the use of templates could make code somewhat less portable.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Support may also be poor when a C++ compiler is being used with a linker that is not C++-aware, or when attempting to use templates across shared library boundaries.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Compilers can produce confusing, long, and sometimes unhelpful error messages when errors are detected in code that uses SFINAE.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] This can make templates difficult to develop with.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Finally, the use of templates requires the compiler to generate a separate *instance* of the templated class or function for every type parameters used with it.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] (This is necessary because types in C++ are not all the same size, and the sizes of data fields are important to how classes work.) So the indiscriminate use of templates can lead to code bloat, resulting in excessively large executables.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] However, judicious use of template specialization and derivation can dramatically reduce such code bloat in some cases:So, can derivation be used to reduce the problem of code replicated because templates are used?
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] This would involve deriving a template from an ordinary class.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] This technique proved successful in curbing code bloat in real use.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Templated classes or functions may require an *explicit specialization* of the template class which would require rewriting of an entire class for a specific template parameters used by it.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] The extra instantiations generated by templates can also cause some debuggers to have difficulty working gracefully with templates.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] For example, setting a debug breakpoint within a template from a source file may either miss setting the breakpoint in the actual instantiation desired or may set a breakpoint in every place the template is instantiated.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Also, the implementation source code for the template must be completely available (e.g. included in a header) to the translation unit (source file) using it.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Templates, including much of the Standard Library, if not included in header files, cannot be compiled.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] (This is in contrast to non-templated code, which may be compiled to binary, providing only a declarations header file for code using it.) This may be a disadvantage by exposing the implementing code, which removes some abstractions, and could restrict its use in closed-source projects.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] The D language supports templates based in design on C++.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Templates in D use a different syntax than in C++: whereas in C++ template parameters are wrapped in angular brackets (`Template<param1, param2>`), D uses an exclamation sign and parentheses: `Template!(param1, param2)`.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] This avoids the C++ parsing difficulties due to ambiguity with comparison operators.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] If there is only one parameter, the parentheses can be omitted.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Conventionally, D combines the above features to provide compile-time polymorphism using trait-based generic programming.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Combining the above allows generating code based on existing declarations.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] For example, D serialization frameworks can enumerate a type's members and generate specialized functions for each serialized type to perform serialization and deserialization.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] User-defined attributes could further indicate serialization rules.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] The `import` expression and compile-time function execution also allow efficiently implementing domain-specific languages.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Generic classes have been a part of Eiffel since the original method and language design.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] The foundation publications of Eiffel, use the term *genericity* to describe creating and using generic classes.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Generic classes are declared with their class name and a list of one or more *formal generic parameters*.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] The formal generic parameters are placeholders for arbitrary class names that will be supplied when a declaration of the generic class is made, as shown in the two *generic derivations* below, where `ACCOUNT` and `DEPOSIT` are other class names.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] `ACCOUNT` and `DEPOSIT` are considered *actual generic parameters* as they provide real class names to substitute for `G` in actual use.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Within the Eiffel type system, although class `LIST [G]` is considered a class, it is not considered a type.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] However, a generic derivation of `LIST [G]` such as `LIST [ACCOUNT]` is considered a type.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] For the list class shown above, an actual generic parameter substituting for `G` can be any other available class.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] To constrain the set of classes from which valid actual generic parameters can be chosen, a *generic constraint* can be specified.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] In the declaration of class `SORTED_LIST` below, the generic constraint dictates that any valid actual generic parameter will be a class that inherits from class `COMPARABLE`.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] The generic constraint ensures that elements of a `SORTED_LIST` can in fact be sorted.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Support for the *generics*, or "containers-of-type-T" was added to the Java programming language in 2004 as part of J2SE 5.0.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] In Java, generics are only checked at compile time for type correctness.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] The generic type information is then removed via a process called type erasure, to maintain compatibility with old JVM implementations, making it unavailable at runtime.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] For example, a `List<String>` is converted to the raw type `java.util.List`.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] The compiler inserts type casts to convert the elements to the `java.lang.String` type when they are retrieved from the list, reducing performance compared to other implementations such as C++ templates.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Generics were added as part of .NET Framework 2.0 in November 2005, based on a research prototype from Microsoft Research started in 1999.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Although similar to generics in Java, .NET generics do not apply type erasure, but implement generics as a first class mechanism in the runtime using reification.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] This design choice provides additional functionality, such as allowing reflection with preservation of generic types, and alleviating some of the limits of erasure (such as being unable to create generic arrays).
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] This also means that there is no performance hit from runtime casts and normally expensive boxing conversions.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] When primitive and value types are used as generic arguments, they get specialized implementations, allowing for efficient generic collections and methods.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] As in C++ and Java, nested generic types such as `Dictionary<string, List<int>>` are valid types, however are advised against for member signatures in code analysis design rules.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] .NET allows six varieties of generic type constraints using the `where` keyword including restricting generic types to be value types, to be classes, to have constructors, and to implement interfaces.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] The `MakeAtLeast()` method allows operation on arrays, with elements of generic type `T`.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] The method's type constraint indicates that the method is applicable to any type `T` that implements the generic `System.IComparable<T>` interface.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] This ensures a compile time error, if the method is called if the type does not support comparison.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] The interface provides the generic method `CompareTo(T)`.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] The above method could also be written without generic types, simply using the non-generic `System.Array` type.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] However, since arrays are contravariant, the casting would not be type safe, and the compiler would be unable to find certain possible errors that would otherwise be caught when using generic types.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] In addition, the method would need to access the array items as `object`s instead, and would require casting to compare two elements.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] A notable behavior of static members in a generic .NET class is static member instantiation per run-time type (see example below).
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] For Pascal, generics were first implemented in 2006, in the implementation Free Pascal.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] The Object Pascal dialect Delphi acquired generics in the 2007 Delphi 11 release by CodeGear, initially only with the .NET compiler (since discontinued) before being added to the native code in the 2009 Delphi 12 release.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] The semantics and abilities of Delphi generics are largely modelled on those of generics in .NET 2.0, though the implementation is by necessity quite different.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] As with C#, methods and whole types can have one or more type parameters.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] In the example, TArray is a generic type (defined by the language) and MakeAtLeast a generic method.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] The available constraints are very similar to the available constraints in C#: any value type, any class, a specific class or interface, and a class with a parameterless constructor.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Multiple constraints act as an additive union.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Free Pascal implemented generics in 2006 in version 2.2.0, before Delphi and with different syntax and semantics.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] However, since FPC version 2.6.0, the Delphi-style syntax is available when using the language mode `{$mode Delphi}`.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Thus, Free Pascal code supports generics in either style.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] The type class mechanism of Haskell supports generic programming.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] All the necessary methods will be "derived" – that is, constructed automatically – based on the structure of the type.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] This results in an equality function (`==`) and a string representation function (`show`) being automatically defined for any type of the form `BinTree T` provided that `T` itself supports those operations.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Ralf Hinze (2004) has shown that a similar effect can be achieved for user-defined type classes by certain programming techniques.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Other researchers have proposed approaches to this and other kinds of genericity in the context of Haskell and extensions to Haskell (discussed below).
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] PolyP was the first generic programming language extension to Haskell.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] In PolyP, generic functions are called *polytypic*.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] The language introduces a special construct in which such polytypic functions can be defined via structural induction over the structure of the pattern functor of a regular datatype.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Regular datatypes in PolyP are a subset of Haskell datatypes.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] A regular datatype t must be of kind ** → **, and if *a* is the formal type argument in the definition, then all recursive calls to *t* must have the form *t a*.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] These restrictions rule out higher-kinded datatypes and nested datatypes, where the recursive calls are of a different form.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Generic Haskell is another extension to Haskell, developed at Utrecht University in the Netherlands.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] The resulting type-indexed value can be specialized to any type.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Clean offers generic programming based PolyP and the Generic Haskell as supported by the GHC ≥ 6.0.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] It parametrizes by kind as those but offers overloading.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Languages in the ML family support generic programming through parametric polymorphism and generic modules called *functors.* Both Standard ML and OCaml provide functors, which are similar to class templates and to Ada's generic packages.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Scheme syntactic abstractions also have a connection to genericity – these are in fact a superset of C++ templates.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] A Verilog module may take one or more parameters, to which their actual values are assigned upon the instantiation of the module.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] One example is a generic register array where the array width is given via a parameter.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Such an array, combined with a generic wire vector, can make a generic buffer or memory module with an arbitrary bit width out of a single module implementation.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] VHDL, being derived from Ada, also has generic abilities.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] C has a feature called "type-generic expressions" using the `_Generic` keyword: This feature gives C function overloading capabilities, but is not related to generic programming.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Generic programming can be achieved by using the preprocessor to define the generic code, with macro expansion taking the role of *instantiation*.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/generic-programming] Sometimes, the non-standard extension "statement expressions" is used to simulate function-like behaviour for generic code.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/kind-type-theory] In the area of mathematical logic and computer science known as type theory, a **kind** is the type of a type constructor or, less commonly, the type of a higher-order type operator (type constructor).
[src:parametric-polymorphism/kind-type-theory] A kind system is essentially a simply typed lambda calculus "one level up", endowed with a primitive type, usually denoted * and called "type", which is the kind of any data type that does not need any type parameters.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/kind-type-theory] Syntactically, it is natural to consider polymorphic data types to be type constructors, thus non-polymorphic types to be nullary type constructors.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/kind-type-theory] But all nullary constructors, thus all monomorphic types, have the same, simplest kind; namely * .
[src:parametric-polymorphism/kind-type-theory] This is essentially a stratified type theory approach, in the style of Leivant's stratified system F, a predicative variant of Girard's impredicative system F.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/kind-type-theory] Since higher-order type operators are uncommon in programming languages, in most programming practice, kinds are used to distinguish between data types and the types of constructors which are used to implement parametric polymorphism.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/kind-type-theory] Kinds appear, either explicitly or implicitly, in languages whose type systems account for parametric polymorphism in a programmatically accessible way, such as C++, Haskell, and Scala.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/kind-type-theory] ML-polymorphism coincides with rank-1 polymorphism in Leivant's stratification, thus kinds are not explicitly present in ML, although theoretical presentations of ML's type inference algorithm sometimes do use kinds.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/kind-type-theory] This is useful for instance when record types (and row polymorphism) are introduced, because the record type constructor is basically a partial function; it does not allow for instance labels to be repeated.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/kind-type-theory] This restriction can be expressed as the row kind being parametrized by a set of labels.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/kind-type-theory] Haskell98 had mostly untyped kinds, thus kinds in Haskell98 are more of an arity specifier.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/kind-type-theory] For instance, taking the usual option generics as example, it could distinguish between the kind of the constructor `Maybe` of kind `* -> *` and `Maybe Int` (for instance) of kind `*`, but the arrow was essentially the only kind constructor.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/kind-type-theory] Around 2010, this was approach was deemed unsatisfactory, especially with the introduction of GADTs in the language, because the untyped stratification prevented the "promotion" (or equal treatment) of kind equations on par with type equations in a GADT context.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/kind-type-theory] Consequently Haskell (around GHC 7.4) added "promoted datatypes", in which a type is automatically mirrored to a kind.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/kind-type-theory] Its proponents deemed it a resonable compromise between Haskell98 and adding full-fledged dependent types.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/kind-type-theory] Haskell documentation uses the same arrow for both function *types* and *kinds*.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/kind-type-theory] An inhabited type (as proper types are called in Haskell) is a type which has values.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/kind-type-theory] For example, ignoring type classes which complicate the picture, `4` is a value of type `Int`, while `[1, 2, 3]` is a value of type `[Int]` (list of Ints).
[src:parametric-polymorphism/kind-type-theory] Therefore, `Int` and `[Int]` have kind * , but so does any function type, for example `Int -> Bool` or even `Int -> Int -> Bool`.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/kind-type-theory] A type constructor takes one or more type arguments, and produces a data type when enough arguments are supplied, i.e. it supports partial application thanks to currying.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/kind-type-theory] This is how Haskell achieves parametric types.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/kind-type-theory] For example, the type `[]` (list) is a type constructor - it takes a single argument to specify the type of the elements of the list.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/kind-type-theory] Hence, `[Int]` (list of Ints), `[Float]` (list of Floats) and even `[[Int]]` (list of lists of Ints) are valid applications of the `[]` type constructor.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/kind-type-theory] Therefore, `[]` is a type of kind $*\rightarrow *$ .
[src:parametric-polymorphism/kind-type-theory] Because `Int` has kind * , applying `[]` to it results in `[Int]`, of kind * .
[src:parametric-polymorphism/kind-type-theory] The 2-tuple constructor `(,)` has kind $*\rightarrow *\rightarrow *$ , the 3-tuple constructor `(,,)` has kind $*\rightarrow *\rightarrow *\rightarrow *$ and so on.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/kind-type-theory] Standard Haskell does not allow polymorphic kinds, in contrast to parametric polymorphism on types, which Haskell supports.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/kind-type-theory] the kind of `z` could be anything, including * , but also $*\rightarrow *$ etc.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/kind-type-theory] Haskell by default will always infer kinds to be * , unless the type explicitly indicates otherwise (see below).
[src:parametric-polymorphism/kind-type-theory] because the kind of `[]`, $*\rightarrow *$ does not match the expected kind for `z`, which is always * .
[src:parametric-polymorphism/kind-type-theory] Higher-order type operators are allowed however.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/kind-type-theory] has kind $(*\rightarrow *)\rightarrow *\rightarrow *$ , i.e.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/kind-type-theory] `unt` is expected to be a unary data constructor, which gets applied to its argument, which must be a type, and returns another type.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/kind-type-theory] Glasgow Haskell Compiler (GHC) has the extension `PolyKinds`, which, together with `KindSignatures`, allows polymorphic kinds.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/kind-type-theory] Since GHC 8.0.1, types and kinds are merged.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/kind-type-theory] At the introduction of unboxed types in GHC, these were abstracted to the `#` kind, different from the `*` kind of boxed types.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/kind-type-theory] And there was no subkinding relation between the two, meaning for instance that a partially applied polymorphic function, which was always inferred to be over boxed types, could not be applied to unboxed types.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/kind-type-theory] In GHC 8.2 this approach was changed to use kind polymorphism instead.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/kind-type-theory] There is a new `TYPE` constructor that is used to classify types, and the old `*` kind, now aliased to `Type` is defined as `TYPE LiftedRep`, while a boxed type like `Int#` is defined as `TYPE IntRep`.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/kind-type-theory] The most general type of the polymorphic function constructor is henceforth `TYPE r1 → TYPE r2 → Type` in GHC 8.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/kind-type-theory] This approach is dubbed "levity polymorphism".
[src:parametric-polymorphism/kind-type-theory] Levity-polymorphic types cannot be inferred in GHC, only type checked.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/kind-type-theory] This is because the most general type for such functions is un-compilable (due to unknown calling convention details for the arguments), so the loss of principal types (for them) is inevitable.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/parametric-polymorphism] In programming languages and type theory, **parametric polymorphism** allows a single piece of code to be given a "generic" type, using variables in place of actual types, and then instantiated with particular types as needed.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/parametric-polymorphism] Parametrically polymorphic functions and data types are sometimes called **generic functions** and **generic datatypes**, respectively, and they form the basis of generic programming.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/parametric-polymorphism] Parametric polymorphism may be contrasted with ad hoc polymorphism.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/parametric-polymorphism] Parametrically polymorphic definitions are *uniform*: they behave identically regardless of the type they are instantiated at.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/parametric-polymorphism] In contrast, ad hoc polymorphic definitions are given a distinct definition for each type.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/parametric-polymorphism] Thus, ad hoc polymorphism can generally only support a limited number of such distinct types, since a separate implementation has to be provided for each type.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/parametric-polymorphism] The usual theoretical device for studying parametric polymorphism is system F, which extends simply typed lambda calculus with quantification over types.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/parametric-polymorphism] It is possible to write functions that do not depend on the types of their arguments.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/parametric-polymorphism] For example, the identity function ${\mathsf {id}}(x)=x$ simply returns its argument unmodified.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/parametric-polymorphism] This naturally gives rise to a family of potential types, such as ${\mathsf {Int}}\to {\mathsf {Int}}$ , ${\mathsf {Bool}}\to {\mathsf {Bool}}$ , ${\mathsf {String}}\to {\mathsf {String}}$ , and so on.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/parametric-polymorphism] The polymorphic definition can then be *instantiated* by substituting any concrete type for $\alpha$ , yielding the full family of potential types.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/parametric-polymorphism] The identity function is a particularly extreme example, but many other functions also benefit from parametric polymorphism.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/parametric-polymorphism] For example, an ${\mathsf {append}}$ function that concatenates two lists does not inspect the elements of the list, only the list structure itself.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/parametric-polymorphism] Therefore, ${\mathsf {append}}$ can be given a similar family of types, such as $[{\mathsf {Int}}]\times [{\mathsf {Int}}]\to [{\mathsf {Int}}]$ , $[{\mathsf {Bool}}]\times [{\mathsf {Bool}}]\to [{\mathsf {Bool}}]$ , and so on, where $[T]$ denotes a list of elements of type T .
[src:parametric-polymorphism/parametric-polymorphism] which can be instantiated to any type in the family.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/parametric-polymorphism] Parametrically polymorphic functions like ${\mathsf {id}}$ and ${\mathsf {append}}$ are said to be *parameterized over* an arbitrary type $\alpha$ .
[src:parametric-polymorphism/parametric-polymorphism] Both ${\mathsf {id}}$ and ${\mathsf {append}}$ are parameterized over a single type, but functions may be parameterized over arbitrarily many types.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/parametric-polymorphism] In the expression ${\mathsf {fst}}((3,{\mathsf {true}}))$ , $\alpha$ is instantiated to ${\mathsf {Int}}$ and $\beta$ is instantiated to ${\mathsf {Bool}}$ in the call to ${\mathsf {fst}}$ , so the type of the overall expression is ${\mathsf {Int}}$ .
[src:parametric-polymorphism/parametric-polymorphism] The syntax used to introduce parametric polymorphism varies significantly between programming languages.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/parametric-polymorphism] For example, in some programming languages, such as Haskell, the $\forall \alpha$ quantifier is implicit and may be omitted.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/parametric-polymorphism] Other languages require types to be instantiated explicitly at some or all of a parametrically polymorphic function's call sites.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/parametric-polymorphism] Parametric polymorphism was first introduced to programming languages in ML in 1975.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/parametric-polymorphism] Today it exists in Standard ML, OCaml, F#, Ada, Haskell, Mercury, Visual Prolog, Scala, Julia, Python, TypeScript, C++ and others.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/parametric-polymorphism] Java, C#, Visual Basic .NET and Delphi have each introduced "generics" for parametric polymorphism.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/parametric-polymorphism] Some implementations of type polymorphism are superficially similar to parametric polymorphism while also introducing ad hoc aspects.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/parametric-polymorphism] One example is C++ template specialization.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/parametric-polymorphism] In the 1980s, Leivant introduced a stratified (i.e. predicative) version of Girard and Reynold's system F.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/parametric-polymorphism] Leivant's approach is based on a notion of rank of the quantifiers, which measures their nesting depth inside function constructors.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/parametric-polymorphism] The ML approach is limited to rank-1 polymorphism in this perspective.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/parametric-polymorphism] Haskell has adopted higher-rank parametric polymorphism in the 1990s.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/parametric-polymorphism] For example, rank-2 parametric polymorphism is used in Haskell to define the `runST` monad, which effectively simulates a type and effect system, with "isolated regions of imperative programming".
[src:parametric-polymorphism/parametric-polymorphism] At type level, state isolation essentially stems from the deeper, rank-2 quantification over state in `runST`.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/parametric-polymorphism] (This is not enough to formally describe the runtime semantics of `runST`.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/parametric-polymorphism] A type is said to be of rank *k* (for some fixed integer *k*) if no path from its root to a $\forall$ quantifier passes to the left of *k* or more arrows, when the type is drawn as a tree.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/parametric-polymorphism] A type system is said to support rank-*k* polymorphism if it admits types with rank less than or equal to *k*.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/parametric-polymorphism] For example, a type system that supports rank-2 polymorphism would allow $(\forall \alpha .\alpha \rightarrow \alpha )\rightarrow T$ but not $((\forall \alpha .\alpha \rightarrow \alpha )\rightarrow T)\rightarrow T$ .
[src:parametric-polymorphism/parametric-polymorphism] A type system that admits types of arbitrary rank is said to be "rank-*n* polymorphic".
[src:parametric-polymorphism/parametric-polymorphism] In a *predicative* type system (also known as a *prenex polymorphic* system), type variables may not be instantiated with polymorphic types.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/parametric-polymorphism] Predicative type theories include Martin-Löf type theory and Nuprl.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/parametric-polymorphism] This is very similar to what is called "ML-style" or "Let-polymorphism" (technically ML's Let-polymorphism has a few other syntactic restrictions).
[src:parametric-polymorphism/parametric-polymorphism] This restriction makes the distinction between polymorphic and non-polymorphic types very important; thus in predicative systems polymorphic types are sometimes referred to as *type schemas* to distinguish them from ordinary (monomorphic) types, which are sometimes called *monotypes*.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/parametric-polymorphism] A consequence of predicativity is that all types can be written in a form that places all quantifiers at the outermost (prenex) position.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/parametric-polymorphism] In order to apply this function to a pair of lists, a concrete type T must be substituted for the variable $\alpha$ such that the resulting function type is consistent with the types of the arguments.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/parametric-polymorphism] In an *impredicative* system, T may be any type whatsoever, including a type that is itself polymorphic; thus ${\mathsf {append}}$ can be applied to pairs of lists with elements of any type—even to lists of polymorphic functions such as ${\mathsf {append}}$ itself.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/parametric-polymorphism] Polymorphism in the language ML is predicative.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/parametric-polymorphism] This is because predicativity, together with other restrictions, makes the type system simple enough that full type inference is always possible.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/parametric-polymorphism] As a practical example, OCaml (a descendant or dialect of ML) performs type inference and supports impredicative polymorphism, but in some cases when impredicative polymorphism is used, the system's type inference is incomplete unless some explicit type annotations are provided by the programmer.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/parametric-polymorphism] Some type systems support an impredicative function type constructor even though other type constructors remain predicative.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/parametric-polymorphism] For example, the type $(\forall \alpha .\alpha \rightarrow \alpha )\rightarrow T$ is permitted in a system that supports higher-rank polymorphism, even though $[\forall \alpha .\alpha \rightarrow \alpha ]$ may not be.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/parametric-polymorphism] Type inference for rank-2 polymorphism is decidable, but for rank-3 and above, it is not.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/parametric-polymorphism] In type theory, the most frequently studied impredicative typed λ-calculi are based on those of the lambda cube, especially System F.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/parametric-polymorphism] Leivant's notion of rank can be generalized to symbols other than quantifiers with a simple, suitable substitution.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/parametric-polymorphism] For example, it can be applied to the (constructor of) intersection types.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/parametric-polymorphism] However, the rank-based type hierarchy that results can have different properties.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/parametric-polymorphism] For instance, type inference for rank-3 and above system F remains undecidable (as detailed above), however, for intersection types, type inference is decidable for all finite ranks.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/parametric-polymorphism] In 1985, Luca Cardelli and Peter Wegner recognized the advantages of allowing *bounds* on the type parameters.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/parametric-polymorphism] Many operations require some knowledge of the data types, but can otherwise work parametrically.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/parametric-polymorphism] For example, to check whether an item is included in a list, we need to compare the items for equality.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/parametric-polymorphism] In Standard ML, type parameters of the form *’’a* are restricted so that the equality operation is available, thus the function would have the type *’’a* × *’’a* list → bool and *’’a* can only be a type with defined equality.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/parametric-polymorphism] In Haskell, bounding is achieved by requiring types to belong to a type class; thus the same function has the type ${\textstyle \mathrm {Eq} \,\alpha \,\Rightarrow \alpha \,\rightarrow \left[\alpha \right]\rightarrow \mathrm {Bool} }$ in Haskell.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/parametric-polymorphism] In most object-oriented programming languages that support parametric polymorphism, parameters can be constrained to be subtypes of a given type (see the articles Subtype polymorphism and Generic programming).
[src:parametric-polymorphism/template-c] In plain terms, a templated class or function would be the equivalent of (before "compiling") copying and pasting the templated block of code where it is used, and then replacing the template parameter with the actual one.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/template-c] For this reason, classes employing templated methods place the implementation in the headers (*.h files) as no symbol could be compiled without knowing the type beforehand.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/template-c] The C++ Standard Library provides many useful functions within a framework of connected templates.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/template-c] Major inspirations for C++ templates were the parameterized modules provided by the language CLU and the generics provided by Ada.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/template-c] There are three kinds of templates: *function templates*, *class templates* and, since C++14, *variable templates*.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/template-c] Since C++11, templates may be either variadic or non-variadic; in earlier versions of C++ they are always non-variadic.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/template-c] A *function template* behaves like a function except that the template can accept arguments of various types, enabling type-generic behavior (see example).
[src:parametric-polymorphism/template-c] In other words, a function template represents a family of functions.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/template-c] Both expressions have the same meaning and behave in exactly the same way.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/template-c] The latter form was introduced to avoid confusion, since a type parameter need not be a class until C++20.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/template-c] For example, the C++ Standard Library contains the function template `max(x, y)` which returns the larger of `x` and `y`.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/template-c] This single function definition works with many data types.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/template-c] Specifically, it works with all data types for which **<** (the less-than operator) is defined and returns a value with a type convertible to `bool`.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/template-c] The usage of a function template saves space in the source code file in addition to limiting changes to one function description and making the code easier to read.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/template-c] An instantiated function template usually produces the same object code, though, compared to writing separate functions for all the different data types used in a specific program.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/template-c] For example, if a program uses both an `int` and a `double` version of the `max()` function template above, the compiler will create an object code version of `max()` that operates on `int` arguments and another object code version that operates on `double` arguments.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/template-c] The compiler output will be identical to what would have been produced if the source code had contained two separate non-templated versions of `max()`, one written to handle `int` and one written to handle `double`.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/template-c] In the first two cases, the template argument `T` is automatically deduced by the compiler to be `int` and `double`, respectively.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/template-c] In the third case automatic deduction of `max(3, 7.0)` would fail because the type of the parameters must in general match the template arguments exactly.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/template-c] Therefore, we explicitly instantiate the `double` version with `max<double>()`.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/template-c] This function template can be instantiated with any copy-constructible type for which the expression `y < x` is valid.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/template-c] For user-defined types, this implies that the less-than operator (`<`) must be overloaded in the type.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/template-c] Since C++20, using `auto` or `concept auto` in any of the parameters of a function declaration, that declaration becomes an *abbreviated function template* declaration.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/template-c] A class template provides a specification for generating classes based on parameters.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/template-c] Class templates are generally used to implement containers.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/template-c] A class template is instantiated by passing a given set of types to it as template arguments.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/template-c] The C++ Standard Library contains many class templates, in particular the containers adapted from the Standard Template Library, such as `vector`.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/template-c] Although templating on types, as in the examples above, is the most common form of templating in C++, it is also possible to template on values.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/template-c] can be instantiated with a specific `int`.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/template-c] As a real-world example, the standard library fixed-size array type `std::array` is templated on both a type (representing the type of object that the array holds) and a number which is of type `std::size_t` (representing the number of elements the array holds).
[src:parametric-polymorphism/template-c] When a function or class is instantiated from a template, a specialization of that template is created by the compiler for the set of arguments used, and the specialization is referred to as being a generated specialization.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/template-c] Sometimes, the programmer may decide to implement a special version of a function (or class) for a given set of template type arguments which is called an explicit specialization.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/template-c] In this way certain template types can have a specialized implementation that is optimized for the type or a more meaningful implementation than the generic implementation.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/template-c] Explicit specialization is used when the behavior of a function or class for particular choices of the template parameters must deviate from the generic behavior: that is, from the code generated by the main template, or templates.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/template-c] C++11 introduced variadic templates, which can take a variable number of arguments in a manner somewhat similar to variadic functions such as `std::printf`.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/template-c] Because only C-style variadic parameters are supported in C++, the only way to get type-safe variadic functions (like in Java) is through variadic templates.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/template-c] C++11 introduced template aliases, which act like parameterized typedefs.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/template-c] The following code shows renaming `std::map` to `TreeMap` and `std::unordered_map` to `HashMap`, as well as creating an alias `StringHashMap` for `std::unordered_map<K, std::string>`.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/template-c] This allows, for example, `StringHashMap<int>` to be used as shorthand for `std::unordered_map<int, std::string>`.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/template-c] Since C++20, templates can be constrained similarly to generics wildcards in Java or C# and Rust `where` clauses.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/template-c] This is done using concepts, which represent a set of boolean predicates evaluated at compile time.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/template-c] For example, this code uses `std::derived_from<Derived, Based>` as an upper inheritance bound.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/template-c] A class satisfies this concept if it inherits from `Player`, and classes that do not cannot be used as the template parameter in `processListOfPlayers()`.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/template-c] Concepts can be used to implement a form of type-safe variadic parameters.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/template-c] Furthermore, to constrain these to any specific type, the `std::same_as<T, U>` and `std::convertible_to<T, U>` concepts may be used.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/template-c] For instance, the Java signatures `void foo(int... args);` and `void bar(String... args);` could be written as `void foo(same_as<int> auto... args);` and `void bar(convertible_to<string> auto... args);` respectively.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/template-c] In C++03, "exported templates" were added to C++.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/template-c] These were later removed in C++11, due to very few compilers actually supporting the feature.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/template-c] The only compiler known to support exported templates was Comeau C/C++.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/template-c] An "exported template" is essentially a class template whose static data members and non-inline methods are exported.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/template-c] It must be marked by the keyword `export`.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/template-c] What distinguishes an "exported template" is the fact that it does not need to be defined in a translation unit that uses the template.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/template-c] With the introduction of modules in C++20, the keyword `export` was re-added to C++.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/template-c] The compilation speed benefits intended to be offered by exported templates are offered by modules anyway, making the feature essentially obsolete and superseded by modules.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/template-c] Initially, the concept of templates was not included in some languages, such as Java and C# 1.0.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/template-c] Java's adoption of generics mimics the behavior of templates, but is technically different.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/template-c] C# added generics (parameterized types) in .NET 2.0.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/template-c] The generics in Ada predate C++ templates.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/template-c] Although C++ templates, Java generics, and .NET generics are often considered similar, generics only mimic the basic behavior of C++ templates.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/template-c] In C++ templates, compile-time cases were historically performed by pattern matching over the template arguments.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/template-c] For example, the template base class in the Factorial example below is implemented by matching 0 rather than with an inequality test, which was previously unavailable.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/template-c] However, the arrival in C++11 of standard library features such as `std::conditional` has provided another, more flexible way to handle conditional template instantiation.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/template-c] With these definitions, one can compute, say 6! at compile time using the expression `Factorial<6>::value`.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/template-c] Because of this, template meta-programming is now mostly used to do operations on types.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/type-constructor] In the area of mathematical logic and computer science known as type theory, a **type constructor** is a feature of a typed formal language that builds new types from old ones.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/type-constructor] Basic types are considered to be built using nullary type constructors.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/type-constructor] Some type constructors take another type as an argument, e.g., the constructors for product types, function types, power types and list types.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/type-constructor] New types can be defined by recursively composing type constructors.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/type-constructor] For example, simply typed lambda calculus can be seen as a language with a single non-basic type constructor—the function type constructor.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/type-constructor] Product types can generally be considered "built-in" in typed lambda calculi via currying.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/type-constructor] Abstractly, a type constructor is an *n*-ary **type operator** taking as argument zero or more types, and returning another type.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/type-constructor] Making use of currying, *n*-ary type operators can be (re)written as a sequence of applications of unary type operators.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/type-constructor] For example, giving the structure of the simply-typed λ-calculus at the type level requires binding, or higher-order, type operators.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/type-constructor] These binding type operators correspond to the 2nd axis of the λ-cube, and type theories such as the simply-typed λ-calculus with type operators, λω.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/type-constructor] Combining type operators with the polymorphic λ-calculus (System F) yields System Fω.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/type-constructor] Some functional programming languages make explicit use of type constructors.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/type-constructor] A notable example is Haskell, in which all `data` type declarations are considered to declare type constructors, and basic types (or nullary type constructors) are called type constants.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/type-constructor] Type constructors may also be considered as parametric polymorphic data types.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/type-family] In computer science, a **type family** associates data types with other data types, using a type-level function defined by an open-ended collection of valid instances of input types and the corresponding output types.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/type-family] Type families are a feature of some type systems that allow partial functions between types to be defined by pattern matching.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/type-family] This is in contrast to data type constructors, which define injective functions from all types of a particular kind to a new set of types, and type synonyms (a.k.a. typedef), which define functions from all types of a particular kind to another existing set of types using a single case.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/type-family] Type families and type classes are closely related: normal type classes define partial functions from types to a collection of named *values* by pattern matching on the input types, while type families define partial functions from types to *types* by pattern matching on the input types.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/type-family] In fact, in many uses of type families there is a single type class which logically contains both values and types associated with each instance.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/type-family] A type family declared inside a type class is called an **associated type**.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/type-family] Programming languages with support for type families or similar features include Haskell (with a common language extension), Standard ML (through its module system), Rust, Scala (under the name "abstract types"), and C++ (through use of typedefs in templates).
[src:parametric-polymorphism/type-family] The `TypeFamilies` extension in the Glasgow Haskell Compiler supports both *type synonym families* and *data families*.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/type-family] Type synonym families are the more flexible (but harder to type-check) form, permitting the types in the codomain of the type function to be any type whatsoever with the appropriate kind.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/type-family] Data families, on the other hand, restrict the codomain by requiring each instance to define a new type constructor for the function's result.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/type-family] This ensures that the function is injective, allowing clients' contexts to deconstruct the type family and obtain the original argument type.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/type-family] Type families are useful in abstracting patterns where a common "organization" or "structure" of types is repeated, but with different specific types in each case.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/type-family] Typical use cases include describing abstract data types like generic collections, or design patterns like model–view–controller.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/type-family] One of the original motivations for the introduction of associated types was to allow abstract data types to be parameterized by their content type such that the data structure implementing the abstract type varies in a "self-optimizing" way.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/type-family] Normal algebraic data type parameters can only describe data structures that behave uniformly with respect to all argument types.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/type-family] Associated types, however, can describe a family of data structures that have a uniform interface but vary in implementation according to one or more type parameters.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/type-family] Instances can then be defined for this class, which define both the data structure used and the operations on the data structure in a single location.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/type-family] For efficiency, we might use a packed bit vector representation for arrays of Boolean values, while using a normal array data structure for integer values.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/type-family] The data structure for arrays of ordered pairs is defined recursively as a pair of arrays of each of the element types.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/type-family] With these definitions, when a client refers to an `Array (Int, Bool)`, an implementation is automatically selected using the defined instances.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/type-family] In this example, the use of a type synonym family instead of a data family is essential, since multiple collection types may have the same element type.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/type-family] Functional dependencies are another type system feature that have similar uses to associated types.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/type-family] While an associated type adds a named type function mapping the enclosing type class's parameters to another type, a functional dependency lists the result type as another parameter of the type class and adds a constraint between the type parameters (e.g.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/type-family] "parameter *a* uniquely determines parameter *b*", written `a -> b`).
[src:parametric-polymorphism/type-family] The most common uses of functional dependencies can be directly converted to associated types and vice versa.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/type-family] Type families are regarded as being generally easier to type-check than functional dependencies.
[src:parametric-polymorphism/type-family] The main advantages of functional dependencies over type families are in their added flexibility in handling a few unusual cases.
